2021', 'Exhibition view'),
(6, 'Copies of Illusion', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>As mapping evolves with technology towards measurability and accuracy, humans seem to expect more truth and accuracy from maps. Yet both the precision promised by technology and the clear boundaries and markings on maps may be mere illusions. Whether it is Atlantis in Republic or Sandy Island, which until recently was proven not to exist. There are all sorts of phantom islands on the map, and the explorer sails in anticipation to his destination, only to see a lonely sea surface with nothing on it.&nbsp;</p><p>Even though they have never been visited, never been confirmed, or even proven not to exist, the name of a distant island still appeals to people and has remained on the map for a long time. People have even woven landscapes, legends, and travelogues to convince themselves that these are not illusions. The errors of maps are always difficult to correct, and more than the accurate depiction of space, maps are a source of imagination and desire for unknown places, and a bold interpretation based on the objective claims of field measurements.</p><p>In this work, CHEN uses the mechanical construction of an iris aperture as a metaphor for the erroneous illusions on the map. The shape of the aperture is a reference to the human iris, where the blades rotate to adjust the light entering our vision and determine what we see, as in the case of a cartography that claims to be precise and accurate, but is in fact an error of human consciousness.&nbsp;</p><p>The blades of the aperture in this work are transformed into the feathers of Griffin. This legendary beast does not really exist, but has been given various legends. It guards gold mines and treasures in the ancient Scythian poem Arimaspi, and people have even sought out giant fossilised bones as proof that it once existed. The feathers opening and closing gently on the aperture machinery is like a summons from beyond, promising an island far away and unknowable.</p><p>Even today, even though the map has been corrected, the fallacies of the map have been preserved in various forms. These non-existent copies of illusions are left in place as cartographic loopholes and as a reflection of people’s desires for something other than truth and accuracy.</p><p><b></b><br/></p>', '', 'kinetic installation, stainless steel, DC motor, aluminium', 'Copies of Illusion
kinetic installation, stainless steel, DC motor, aluminium
dimensions variable
2021', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view'),
(7, 'Tidal Variations', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>Tidal Variations is a video installation initiated by Taiwanese artist and filmmaker SU Yu-Hsin and her collaboration with Australian dancer and choreographer Angela GOH. The video reflects on possible transformation processes, both on the individual and on the social/collective levels that this pandemic brought about. The transformation starts from the increasing awareness of the wet mechanics of seeing which is composed with the tides, speed of light and Internet infrastructure. The work assembles contributions by music composer TSENG Yun-Fang (Sound), art writer Sonia Fernández Pan (Text), artist WANG Tzu-Ting (Visualization), programmer Ian WU (Code), dancer Angela GOH (Choreography) and artist SU Yu-Hsin (Image).</p><p>&nbsp;Co-commissioned by the Sydney Opera House, the artists dig into the history of the site, re-imagining it—as speculative data centre drifting on water where undersea cables converge, a spaceship afloat on a wet planet, a screen-like surface that reflects water and light, a site of windows through which bodies and water touch, and a sundial for shadows to glide across, mapping light and dark as time. The Sydney Opera House is both an icon and a performance venue, and as such a perfect site for projection of imagination. Tidal Variations is not only site-specific to the Sydney Opera House but also to the screen. The artists take the screen as a site that can be approached in material and embodied ways. These days, we live on and in our screens. Tidal Variations examines the screen as a device for framing the world, a place where windows can open onto vast worlds, an information surface which the outside in the inside.</p><p>The algorithmic composition video that determines tidal patterns reveals itself through its changes and continuations between solidity and fluidity, asserting its presence through motions and the moments of suspensions. The work explores the window as a conceptual device for reframing our human understanding of our being in the world. Under COVID-19, the windows became a symbol of enclosure and isolation. People looked out the window to the street, and also encountered one another as digital framed images. The artists examine Glass Walls and the engineering structure of the Sydney Opera House to map the Internet infrastructure and optical fiber network: the data light crosses the bottom of the sea and reaches the path of people''s glass screens. They attempt to think from the perspective of material imagination in a way to approach isolation and intimacy during the epidemic. Pandemic sparks subsea bandwidth spike, TeleGeography said the global Internet “ bent but—for the most part—did not break.” Undersea cables construct watery conduits from node to node, frame to frame, window to window. It''s a global system that never sleeps, and information behind the black screen continues flowing.&nbsp;</p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Tidal Variations traces the undersea cable routes that connect us through the internet, the same routes that were plotted and laid for trade voyages, colonial routes and the first telephone passages, mirroring and overlaying through time a planetary infrastructure of power and exchange. The windows that we open on our screens would reveal the history of colonialism, trade, and communication, if we could see past the backlit surface.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Water and light, the two substances that enabled life to evolve in the first place, now enable the contemporary technological entanglement upon which we have come to rely. The tide in people’s bodies is highly connected with the data light behind the screen. The internet functions as light being sent through undersea cables, node to node, across the floor of our wet planet. We arrived through water and light as a life-form and species, now we arrive through water and light as spectres of image and sound, travelling far and wide—and deep—to appear as photons and pixels, announced through the familiar ‘ping!’ of a notification. We travel ghostly and dripping, full of light.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Tidal Variations renders and reveals the image, the body, data, and thinking as water and light, reframing the world through a wet mechanics of seeing.</span></p>', '', 'single channel video installation', 'Tidal Variations
single channel video installation
