(8, 'The Weight of Things', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>Science fiction tells us as much about the present as it does about the future. We write about space travel and teleportation because we long for the possibility of something more than our everyday life. “If only in the future I could…” And for the astronauts who have floated weightlessly in the heavens, who have transgressed the boundary between fact and fiction, the weight of gravity must be unbearable, to have once drifted amongst the stars and now be firmly bound to the ground.</p><p>This installation explores this aspirational quality of science fiction. This spirit of invention glistens in both the young child’s eyes as they build robots out of cardboard boxes as well as the mad scientist who dares to imagine. We embrace action and progress, the momentum of experimentation. We look up at the heavens and leap into the air, knowing that we too can fly...</p>', '', 'installation', 'The Weight of Things
installation
dimensions variable
2021', 'The Weight of Things
installation
dimensions variable
2021', 'The Weight of Things
installation
dimensions variable
2021', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view'),
(13, 'Sugar Foot', '4’16”', '', '<p>In 2020, the outbreak of COVID-19 caused a global lockdown and restricted many activities and events in the world.
“Sugar Foot”, off the 2019 album "Juice B Crypts," is from the New York dual-band Battles. The track features Taiwan experimental rock/folk band Prairie WWWW, with their poems chanting, and the distinctive alto tenor vocals of prog-rock singer Jon ANDERSON of Yes. 

The animation is directed by the Japanese animation team AC-bu, contributors to the notoriously bizarre anime satire "Pop Team Epic." 
This music video depicts the ’Great Space Robot Festival’ that unfolds to avenge cancelled festivals and events, hoping that humanity will be able to overcome the crisis and move towards a better world.</p>', '', 'video', 'Sugar Foot
Video
4''16"
2021', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view'),
(14, 'Inverso Mundus', '38’20”', '', '<p>"Inverso Mundus" is a world where chimeras are pets, and the Apocalypse is entertainment.</p><p>Engravings in the genre of “World Upside Down,”  known since the 16th century, depict such scenes as a pig gutting the butcher, a child punishing his teacher, and a beggar in rags magnanimously bestowing alms on a rich man. These engravings contain demons, chimeras, fish flying through the sky, and death itself.&nbsp;</p><p>The title of the work, “Inverso”–both an Italian “reverse, the opposite” and the Old Italian “poetry,”  and “Mundus”–the Latin “world,” hints at a reinterpretation of reality, a poetic vision. In our interpretation, the absurdist scenes from the medieval carnival——characters act out scenes of absurd social utopias and exchange masks, morphing from beggars to rich men, from policemen to thieves. Metrosexual street-cleaners are showering the city with refuse——appears as episodes of contemporary life in a multichannel video installation.</p>', '', 'three-channel HD video, sound', 'Inverso Mundus
three-channel HD video, sound
38''20"
2015', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work'),
(15, 'AIDOL', '83’00”', 'WRITTEN AND DIRECTED BY Lawrence Lek
EXECUTIVE PRODUCER Sadie Coles
ASSISTANT PRODUCER Joni Zhu
COMPUTER GRAPHICS BY Clifford Sage
SCORE BY Lawrence Lek
EDITED BY Andre Corsini
SOUND DESIGN Seth Scott

CAST 
DIVA Xiaoyi Nie
GEOMANCER Joni Zhu
THIEL Steve Goodman
GUO Sophie Guo  
WU Xiaoran Wu
', '<p>Lawrence LEK’s first feature-length film, AIDOL, is a CGI fantasy that revolves around the long and complex struggle between humanity and Artificial Intelligence. Set against the backdrop of rising human-machine tensions, AIDOL follows Diva, a fading superstar who enlists the help of an AI songwriter for her comeback performance at the 2065 eSports Olympics. Fame—in all its allure and emptiness—is set against the bigger contradictions of a post-AI world, a world where originality is sometimes no more than an algorithmic trick and where machines have the capacity for love and suffering.</p>', '', 'HD video, stereo sound', 'AIDOL
HD video, stereo sound
83''00"
2019', 'AIDOL
HD video, stereo sound
83''00"
2019', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view'),
(16, 'Sinofuturism（1839-2046 AD）', '60’00”', '', '<p>"Sinofuturism (1839-2046 AD)" is a video essay exploring the parallels between portrayals of artificial intelligence and Chinese technological development. LEK combines elements of science fiction, documentary melodrama, social realism, and Chinese cosmologies in order to delve into and critique the present-day dilemmas of China and the people of its diaspora. The essay is structured around seven stereotypes found within Chinese society—Computing, Copying, Gaming, Studying, Addiction, Labor, and Gambling.</p>', '', 'HD video, stereo sound', 'Sinofuturism（1839-2046 AD）
HD video, stereo sound
60''00"
2016', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view'),
(17, 'The Ways of Folding Space & Flying', '15’30” ', '', '<p>The title of the work The Ways of Folding Space &amp; Flying stems from the Korean words “chukjibeop” and “bihaengsul.” Originating from Taoist practice, “chukjibeop” means a hypothetical method of folding space and allowing one to travel a substantial distance in a short space of time. The word describes various techniques for rapid movement or could refer to the energy used to contract physical distance.
“Bihaengsul”is another supernatural power to levitate, fly, and travel across time and space.&nbsp;</p><p>The power emerges from one of the oldest human desires to challenge and triumph over the physical limitations of human beings and to reach an unknown realm. In the history of Eastern culture, these ideas have been explored not only as a means of meditative practice but also as methods to reach a state of complete emancipation of both mind and body from physical limitations and natural forces. A method of levitation without the aid of any scientific technique and only through the means of pure mind and body, bihaengsul remains a valid hypothesis.
Both chukjibeop and bihaengsul are archetypes of using mental practice to overcome human limitations through the power of the imagination. These rather ludicrous and illogical ideas closely echo the basis of artistic practice in that they are both a creative manifestation of human desire to surpass the barriers and structures that bind us.&nbsp;</p><p>Within this context, we intend to show the human endeavor to constantly break new ground, challenge the self, and envision the future of art.</p>', '', 'HD video, sound', 'The Ways of Folding Space & Flying
HD video, sound
15''30"
2015', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view'),
(19, 'Battle City Trilogy', '-', '', '<p>“This city is but a castle in the air.” The series, "Battle City Trilogy," takes three historic references out of their contexts—"The Glory of Taiwan," "Economic Miracle," and "Formosa"—in order to rewrite and rearrange them into a set of prophetic stories/allegories. The significance of these phrases is gradually revealed while the temporal aspect of the stories slowly progresses and aggregates.</p>', '', 'videos, e-books, miniature models', 'Battle City Trilogy
videos, e-books, miniature models
2021', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view'),
(31, 'Space Type Generator', 'flexible with projection', '', '<p>This installation will be a showcase of Kiel D. MUTSCHELKNAUS’s various experiments in generative code. The generator combines typography, interaction, and graphics to create a constant flow of motion. The generator will be similar to what is seen on “spacetypegenerator.com” and the artist’s Instagram.

While the work will be similar to these previous examples, it will be adapted for this specific installation.&nbsp;</p><p>Working with the C-LAB Future Media Arts Festival team, he’ll create a custom version of STG to run efficiently and provide visitors with a custom, interactive experience. The user will be able to manipulate the images at a computer connected to the monitors and interact with various motions.</p>', '', 'projection of generative code', 'Space Type Generator
projection of generative code
flexible with projection
2021', 'Details of the work
', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view'),
(32, 'Kepler’s Dream', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>Kepler’s Dream is an aesthetical investigation exploring analog projection technology in combination with computationally created content that is given a physical shape through 3D printing. Inspired by obsolete projection technologies like the overhead projector, especially the episcope, an installation was designed to generate unique imagery and a fascinating experience. Mixing digital aesthetics—parametric and generative shapes—with the qualities of analog projection creates an otherworldly look. Interacting with the installation creates a deeply immersive effect, as the instant reaction of the projection and the infinite frame rate let this fantastical world come to life.

In the design process, it became clear that a shallow depth of field of the projection invites us to explore and decipher. A spherical object was chosen to allow for a seamless exploration with the freedom to move in all directions. The formal aesthetics of the first prototypes evoked associations with the model of the solar system in Mysterium Cosmographicum by Johannes KEPLER, who was thought to have found the geometrical basis of the universe in the platonic bodies.</p><p>Picking up the mysticism created by KEPLER, who also saw the platonic bodies as representations of the elements: fire, water, earth, and air, the projected world embodies an abstract story. This abstract world can be explored in a non-linear way. Following the path of the structures back to the initial platonic bodies, one can find the conclusion in the all connecting dodecahedron.</p>', '', 'installation', 'Kepler’s Dream
installation
dimensions variable
2014', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view'),
(33, 'Heterotopia', 'main video 15’00”, secondary video 1’00” in cycle of 4', 'The work was supported by Arts and Technology: Creative Innovation and Counseling Project.', '<p>Philosopher Michel FOUCAULT proposed the concept of “Heterotopia” in the 1960s. Unlike the fictitious predictions of Utopia where everything is good or Dystopia where everything is terrible, “Heterotopia” refers to a space that exists parallel to the real world, which can also reflect the real-world views from it. By observing Heterotopia, one can better understand the realities due to this characteristic between reality and fiction.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;This project is an extension based on the fundamental concept of Heterotopia. The micro world uses real-world samples to create a realistic scene that exchanges time with scale, whose existence seems real yet illusory. The conversation with the world around us starts from there.</p>', '', 'video, exported images, samples of city peeling', 'Heterotopia
video, exported images, samples of city peeling
main video 15’00”, secondary video 1’00” in cycle of 4
2021
', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work'),
(34, 'Meandering River', '12’00”／200x800x30 cm', '', '<p>Over time, landscapes are gradually shaped by natural forces. Indiscernible to the naked eye, we only perceive one moment at a time. The fluctuations and the rhythmic movement of rivers are a glimpse into the past, as traces provide evidence of the constant transformations that surround us.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;Meandering River is an audiovisual installation comprised of real-time visuals generated by an algorithm and music composed by an AI. This digital artwork makes change perceivable by creating a unique awareness of time. Spanning over multiple screens, the piece reinterprets the shifting behaviors of rivers by visualizing and sonifying their impact on the surface of the earth.&nbsp;</p><p>The audiovisual installation creates a bird’s eye view of a landscape. This orientation conceptualizes a new human perspective on space and time in an attempt to decipher the unpredictable patterns. By experiencing it from an influential perspective, the real-time visuals demonstrate what is happening on a larger scale. Based on a bespoke algorithm, the rippling and oscillating movement inherent in the generated imagery provides a vantage point that transforms an understanding of progress to examine the rhythm of natural forces.&nbsp;</p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">As the evolving patterns of Meandering River emerge, the viewer is left with a humbling sense of the unpredictability of change and the beauty of nature.</span></p>', '', 'audiovisual art installation', 'Meandering River
audiovisual art installation
12’00”／200x800x30 cm
2018', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view'),
(35, 'SoftMachine', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>“Every object, naturally, emerges like Aphrodite from a flux of elements. …Born from this and, as soon as it is born, complex, twined, twisting its long thick hair, it begins to transmit, in floods and in all directions, a star of flow: its wear and its time. It radiates various waves: heat, odors, sounds, simulacra, subtle atoms. In the same way or inversely, it receives the flow emitted around it, from the vicinity and the edges of the open universe alike.”                                                    — Lucretius’ De rerum natura in The Birth of Physics, Michelle SERRES, 1980.

SoftMachine is an electrochemical algorithmic machine performance that probes an alternative computational and technological material regime, informed by Gordon Pask’s experiments on electrochemical learning mechanisms and current research on biomimicry, programmable matter and spatio-temporally controlled liquid metal actuators. A radical technology that bridges traditionally discreet machine thinking and soft/fluid materials that enable self-organizing behavior through their specific material agencies. At its core, a custom-built electrochemical experimental apparatus（SoftMachine）creates a dynamic fluidic microcosm that performs a continuous becoming of form, structure, and material narrations. The performance aims to provoke new imaginaries of the machinic, the artificial and matter.&nbsp;</p><p>SoftMachine is an analog/digital hybrid to speculate about a heterogeneous technological culture. The neo-alchemistic material performance is captured by multiple cameras and composed and displayed in real-time on a projection screen. The visuals are accompanied by a sonic layer, the direct translation of the electrochemical processes taking place in the fluid, a melange of drifting frequencies, pulses, patterns, and noise.</p>', '', 'installation', 'SoftMachine
installation
dimensions variable
2021', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work'),
(36, 'Twin Temples, Moniang’s Hair and Heavenly Hong', '-', 'The work was supported by "Arts and Technology: Creative Innovation and Counseling Project."', '<p>This project is a collaborative project with a hundred-year-old Chinese medicine shop in Hsinchu, Taiwan, aiming to explore the culture of prescription fortune sticks by conducting cross-disciplinary collaboration, field study, and on-site production. The use of prescription fortune sticks is a folk ministration that combines several traditional beliefs reflecting Chinese medical philosophy that the human body and spirit are inter-connected. In the early Taiwanese immigrant society, prescription fortune sticks were used to treat infectious diseases but have since been excluded from modern medical systems, making the ministration a rare practice in modern days.

In the new normal circumstances of a post-pandemic era, the use of prescription fortune sticks can show that diseases reflect an individual’s physical condition and a collective society’s belief system and ideology. In short, Chinese medicine, western medicine, and traditional beliefs should not be mutually exclusive but should co-exist to counterbalance each other.&nbsp;</p>', '', 'mixed media', 'Twin Temples, Moniang’s Hair and Heavenly Hong
mixed media
2021', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work'),
(37, 'Weightless Plan—New Normal', '30’00”', 'The work was supported by "Arts and Technology: Creative Innovation and Counseling Project."', '<p>"Weightless Plan" is TIAN’s project, which initially began in early 2020. The center of this project is to reflect upon how the age of mechanical reproduction has dramatically changed human life and thinking. "Weightless Plan" aims to portray how human minds are gradually losing consciousness and our value standards under the influence of internet data in this material-orientated world. This project also attempts to take the ordinaries created by mechanical reproduction to infiltrate the behavioral psychology of humanity. TIAN incorporates the messages brought by the LCD screen and the foundation of plasma, together with the shattered monitor, to demonstrate the daily information overload and repetitive mechanical operation. Metaphorically, that showcases the damage caused by the violence of technology.</p><p>&nbsp;"Weightless Plan—New Normal" collaborates with the Mailantia Dance Company and attempts to combine the strength and beauty of both technological art and performance art. The goal is to return to the root of technology production and the political essence, thus making dance the post-pandemic symbol of humanity. Applying industrial products, dance, live recording, and audio playback challenge the boundary between technology and body and the Cunningham of the internal image within time and space. The highly experienced dancers make it possible for this interdisciplinary piece to infuse modern dance and street dance and, therefore, experiment with diverse project forms. The most refined synaesthetic for the audiences is possibly the experience of being brought into technology through these physical senses.&nbsp;</p>', '', 'dance, LCD monitors', 'Weightless Plan—New Normal
dance, LCD monitors
30''00"
2021', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work'),
(41, 'iFace DQ', 'Dimension variable', '', '<p>“Face recognition” is gaining in popularity in the application areas of access authentication and public surveillance. Researchers have also studied its controversial use to predict different social behaviors. The artwork "iFace DQ" is a speculative investigation of and critical reflection on using facial recognition technology to parody the patriotic view of the participants, based on a pool of known faces of Hong Kong Legislative Council members. The artwork also assesses the risk of being disqualified should the participants plan to run for the Council election.</p>', '', 'Interactive installation', 'iFace DQ
Interactive installation
Dimension variable
2021', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work'),
(42, 'TFN—Technological Finding Netbot', '300x65x3 cm', '', '<p>"TFN—Technological Finding Netbot" is a joint production of the Taiwan C-LAB Future Media Arts Festival and the Hong Kong Microwave International New Media Arts Festival. The work explores the information of the current high-profile NFT (non-fungible token) trading market. 

The designed web crawler will automatically search for NFT-related information and analyze the keywords, and these picked-out texts are displayed on the large LED electronic scroll board in front of the pillar. The audience can also see the process of how the web crawler searches and analyzes the NFT information on the website.</p><p>In March 2021, after American digital artist Beeple’s digital work "Everydays: The First 5000 Days" was sold for an unprecedentedly high price of US$70 million（about NT$1.9 billion）, it instantly detonated a heated wave of NFT trends. Tweets, videos, a piece of music, and even a digital license for a classical painting could sell at sky-high prices. "TFN—Technological Finding Netbot" also raises the question: Are people only concerned about the soaring prices of NFTs and how to join in the NFT market nowadays?</p>', '', 'installation', 'TFN—Technological Finding Netbot
installation
300x65x3cm
2021', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', ''),
(43, 'The Glass Room (Misinformation Edition) ', '75x75 cm, 75x150 cm, 150x75 cm (posters)', 'https://theglassroom.org/en/misinformation-edition', '<p>In this exhibition, we present Tactical Tech’s newest edition of "The Glass Room (Misinformation Edition)," which explores misinformation in all its forms and aims to demystify technology through immersive, thought-provoking, and self-learning participation. This work finds out about the new types of influencers, the new and old tactics they use, and the role we, the users and consumers, play in the way information flows. All exhibits are presented through a series of animations, visualizations, and apps that can be experienced on desktops and mobile devices. We invite you to take a deep dive beyond your screen and into the world of deepfakes, misinformation, design strategies, and profiling. You can explore how social media and the web have changed the way we read information and react to it.</p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">&nbsp;A growing need for public interventions and information about technology led Tactical Tech to design "The Glass Room (Misinformation Edition)"—a lightweight, pop-up exhibition translated into over fifteen local languages and can be shipped worldwide to community spaces, schools, libraries, and festivals.</span></p>', '', 'printed, digital', 'The Glass Room (Misinformation Edition)
printed, digital
75x75 cm, 75x150 cm, 150x75 cm (posters)
2020', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view'),
(44, 'Memory War', 'dimensions variable', 'The work was supported by "Arts and Technology: Creative Innovation and Counseling Project."', '<p>"Digital Memory Studies," a work by Professor Andrew HOSKINS of the University of Glasgow, explores how in the digital era, users’ reliance on smartphones, search engines, and social media influences how the majority remember things in various ways. He stresses that in the era of digital technology, the ways human beings remember things could be changed forever, as human brains no longer need to actively remember and recall because in the “algorithm era,” one only needs to upload and search to bring anything to mind. 

Based on the above concept,</p><p>"Memory War" explores how the developments of the digital technology era can change the way people remember, playing out scenes of algorithms disturbing the memories of social networks to counter the manipulation of state and digital media power. The online data now carry the majority of civilization’s memories. The passages and memories of our daily life are preserved and recorded on social media, and past events are even “recommended,” re-evoking our recollections ever anew.</p>', '', 'performance art, installation, documentary videos, internet interactive interface', 'Memory War
performance art, installation, documentary videos, internet interactive interface
dimensions variable
2021', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work', 'Details of the work'),
(45, 'Consonance and Dissonance', '20min', '', '<p>A chord is created by three or more notes of different frequencies emitted simultaneously. The resulting sound depends on the pitch ratio of the notes. An overlap of notes close to a simple integer ratio is considered "consonance," and that of a more complex ratio is considered "dissonance.” In Western music, consonance and dissonance correspond to relaxation and tension. When tension is released, a coherent musical structure is created (cadence). Society is also like a chord, with ideas and thoughts of various scales coexisting. Sometimes they harmonize, and sometimes they collide, resulting in a state of dissonance. Dissonance leads to an uneasy psychology and drives consensual resolution. On the one hand, a constant state of harmony is dull and mundane. On the other hand, excessive dissonance leads to tension and anxiety. In this balance between harmony and disharmony, a swell of emotions and stories is perceived, and emotion is born. The concept of harmony expands and encompasses the state of dissonance, dismantling it. In this work, an attempt is made to express tension and relaxation through sounds and images and to reflect on the current social situation.</p>', '', '', 'Atsushi TADOKORO, Consonance and Dissonance, 2021', 'Atsushi TADOKORO, Consonance and Dissonance, 2021', 'Atsushi TADOKORO, Consonance and Dissonance, 2021', 'Atsushi TADOKORO, Consonance and Dissonance, 2021', 'Atsushi TADOKORO, Consonance and Dissonance, 2021'),
(46, 'Transient', '20 min', '', '<p>"Transient" is a full-dome format audiovisual concert. Based on random (stochastic) processes of image and ephemeral sounds evolving within time and space.

Microscopic elements are born from emptiness, moving and pulsating from light and sounds. It becomes a whole new universe within mere seconds. The swirls of particles and noise throb towards infinity, immerse from the screen, and penetrate the viewer’s skin to settle into nothingness and quiet in just an instant.&nbsp;</p><p>The irregular rhythmic textures oscillate through the darkness and radiate with urgency and brevity of the moment. Here and now, another universe explodes and disappears. Its energy transforms into a new life as the circle of nature, scattered through time but carefully preserved by human and computer memories, created in the digital reality to make its emotional impact in a physical space.</p>', '', '', 'Alex GUEVARA, Transient, 2021', 'Alex GUEVARA, Transient, 2021', 'Alex GUEVARA, Transient, 2021', 'Alex GUEVARA, Transient, 2021', ''),
(47, 'L''alter-monde', '24 min', '', 'L’alter-monde is an immersive audiovisual project in fulldome format. As an evocation of a cybernetic garden in multiple scenes, this work contemplates a potential symbiosis between humans and a state of rediscovered nature. Through ecosophy and interspecies mutualism, it explores the possibility of identification with a mutant nature, a plant-becoming state, or the experience of infrahuman lives. In search of a biosensitivity, a non-human/hypernatural sensitivity emerges.
L’alter-monde addresses critical issues of climate change and extinction of species while immersing the viewer in a potentially transformative experience. Through imaginative worldbuilding, intricate visual ramifications, and skillful sound design, this work offers the opportunity for constructive meditation on economic degrowth and the crucial posthuman symbiosis with nature.', '', '', 'Sandrine DEUMIERＸMyriam BLEAU, L''alter-monde, 2020', 'Sandrine DEUMIERＸMyriam BLEAU, L''alter-monde, 2020', 'Sandrine DEUMIERＸMyriam BLEAU, L''alter-monde, 2020', 'Sandrine DEUMIERＸMyriam BLEAU, L''alter-monde, 2020', 'Sandrine DEUMIERＸMyriam BLEAU, L''alter-monde, 2020'),
(48, 'On Earth Series：Dome', '15 mins', 'Project Coordinator｜Nulls Design
Visual Design｜Jie LIOU
Sound Design｜WU Ping-Sheng, Andy CHIU', '<p>On Earth Series is a real-time audiovisual performance. Three years after their first performance in Taipei, Nulls Design brings a combination of new techniques and a unique vibe to search for harmony and relevance between sounds and images while providing an ultra-immersive experience.</p>', '', '', 'Nulls Design, On Earth Series：Dome, 2021', 'Nulls Design, On Earth Series：Dome, 2021', '', '', ''),
(49, 'Reincarnate Island', '15 min', '', '<p>In Taiwan, there is a common folk belief that people have three souls and seven senses. Souls belong to the spiritual world while senses belong to the material world. When the soul leaves the physical body, the senses disappear. Based on this cultural belief, this work attempts to explore the relationships between “souls and senses” and “consciousness and body.” The vaulted performance venue becomes an extension of reality, so that under the transformation of media into a space, a scene for rituals related to collective reincarnation is created. Considering Buddhist and folk beliefs about reincarnation, the viewer is encouraged to visualize the body from the perspective of the soul through an inner landscape diagram of the seven senses. As viewers roam in and out of architecture-like consciousness, they reflect on the relationship between spiritual and material worlds through different interpretations of body and soul in ancient and modern times.</p>', '', '', 'XTRUX, Reincarnate Island, 2021', 'XTRUX, Reincarnate Island, 2021', 'XTRUX, Reincarnate Island, 2021', 'XTRUX, Reincarnate Island, 2021', ''),
(51, 'Re-Generative:: update()', '2 hours', '*A smart phone with earphones is required in order to join this performance. 
*Audiences must follow staff instructions for entry and re-entry during the opening hour of the performance. ', '<p>Continuing developing the generative arts from Re-Generative last year, TASI Chi-Hung, the technical director from C-LAB Technology Media Platform, works with the sound design, Blaire KO, again and creates with generative image works via reaction diffusion and kaleidoscope effect.&nbsp;</p><p>This performance will focus on the audience’s interaction and the sound experiences. Via the immersive sound experiences by earphones, the image is changed in real time according to the state of the audience walking in the space. With the support of high-performance cloud computing from the National Center for High-performance Computing and the remote desktop GPU acceleration, it tries to experiment with the reaction diffusion creating high-resolution generative images. Technology Media Platform, through constituting a cross-disciplinary team, not only shows the professional techniques of software and hardware integration, but also provides immersive audiovisual perceptions to the public in dome.</p>', '', '', 'TSAI Chi-HungＸBlaire KO, Re-Generative, 2020', 'TSAI Chi-HungＸBlaire KO, Re-Generative, 2020', 'TSAI Chi-HungＸBlaire KO, Re-Generative, 2020', '', ''),
(52, 'Immersive Audiovisual Workshop-The Joint Presentation ', '90 mins', 'Department of New Media Art, Taipei National University of the Arts
The Department of New Media Art of Taipei National University of the Arts is the first department of its kind in the country. It breaks through the conventional boundaries of humanities and the arts to integrate cutting-edge technology and serves as an important promoter of the integration of digital technology and art to cultivate forward-looking creative talent in future art domains such as technology, images, and transdisciplinary works.
Lecturers｜YEH Ting-Hao, LI Yi-Fan, WANG Lien-Cheng
Participants｜LIU CHANG Miao-Chi, SHI Kun-Fang, TSAI Shang-Teng
CHEN Pin-Chen, CHEN Cheng-Wei, CHEN Yen-Shan
KAO Ching-Hsuan, Daniel CHIANG, Charlotte HSIEH 

Department of Communications Design, Shih Chien University
Design college of Shih Chien University has been ranked among the top 30 best design schools in the world by Businessweek Weekly and Ranker.com. The Department of Communications Design was established in 1997 and renamed in 2000. It became the first department in Taiwan to be named after the “Communications Design”. Beside the technical training, we dedicate and emphasize the training of design thinking and humanistic aesthetic in general.
Lecturer｜TSAI Tsun-Hung
Participant｜
HSU Yung-Hsin, CHEN Szu-Yu, CHEN Xiang-Hao, LIN Ming-Hong
KO Chung-An, LAN Ko-Yun, CHEN Jou-Min, CHEN Chia-Yin
Vice LEE, CHEN En-Hsuan, CHENG Jung-An, CAO Zhong
CHANG Hsiang-Hua, LI I-Chen, CHEN Shi-Yuan, CHOU Chia-Jen
TSAI Cheng-Ting, LEE Wan-Ru, D·ENNY
HO Sea, CHAO Yung-An, WU Cheng-Tse, HSU Ning-Ju', 'This year, C-LAB Technology Media Platform cooperated with the Department of New Media Art at the Taipei National University of the Arts and the Department of Communications Design, Shih Chien University, and hosted immersive AudioVisual Workshops in June and August. The students, led by YEH Ting-Hao, LI Yi-Fan, WANG Lien-Cheng and TSAI Tsun-Hung, are divided into groups and create immersive audiovisual works. The corporation not only provides performance opportunities for students, but also nurtures the young talent in new media art.', '', '', 'Students'' work-in-progress from Department of New Media Art, Taipei National University of the Arts', 'Students'' work-in-progress from Department of New Media Art, Taipei National University of the Arts', 'Students'' work-in-progress from Department of New Media Art, Taipei National University of the Arts', 'Students'' work-in-progress from Department of Communications Design, Shih Chien University', ''),
(53, 'Ban Shan', '10 min', '*The performance contains smoke and viewer discretion is advised.', '​​Ban Shan — which in the Taiwanese (Hokkien) dialect means “play god” — is a story about a “Ba Jia Jiang”, a young medium who represents the bodyguard of a Taiwanese god.  He has a lucid dream after a temple fair one night in which he dances until he becomes a god. In order to create a temple fair scene, in which Ba Jia Jiang dance in arrays accompanied by the sounds of firecrackers and Taiwanese gongs, a surround sound version of this work was created.  
The composer grew up in an area of Tainan City (Taiwan) populated by temples. This surround sound version of Ban Shan invokes the atmosphere of traditional festivals in her hometown, which she hopes to share with the world.', '', '', 'Sandra TAVALIＸWonderGymＸLIN Yen-Chun, Ban Shan, 2021', 'Sandra TAVALIＸWonderGymＸLIN Yen-Chun, Ban Shan, 2021', 'Sandra TAVALIＸWonderGymＸLIN Yen-Chun, Ban Shan, 2021', '', ''),
(54, 'Flesh Gods', '2 hours', '*The program contains nude, erotic, violence scenes and viewer discretion is advise.
*The age guidance for this performance is 18+ and valid ID is required for entry. 
*Audiences must follow staff instructions for entry and re-entry during the opening hour of the performance. ', '<p>By gazing at the world, creating connections and meaning seem like natural human pursuits. Distant stars forming constellations or the regulation of time-space is described in terms of humankind to broaden the imagination and narratives. Immersive dome projection experiences remind us of the frescoes that decorate religious buildings and serve as bridges to link people and the heavens/the world.</p><p>Flesh Gods is a durational performance that includes some nudity. Performers are inspired by frescoes that adorn religious buildings around the world. To achieve 360-degree cinematography effects, cameras are attached to the performers. Through continuous movement and exploration, flowing images create a giant flesh-dome. As we look up at the sky, we gaze at ourselves.&nbsp;</p><p>Audience members can join the performance to take part in shaping this dome, intervening in and illustrating spontaneous sequences of the cosmos.</p>', '', '', 'Co-coism, Flesh Gods, 2021', '', '', '', ''),
(55, 'Concurrent of Root(s)', '20min', '*The performance contains flashlights and viewer discretion is advised.', '<p>Concurrent of Root(s) is an experimental system which combines generative art and plant growth. By providing a co-owned space, an attempt is made to find out how the Internet affects the human time concept as humans produce connections among and interfere with one another in this unlimited and timeless Internet world.</p>', '', '', 'CHAO Pei-Yu, Concurrent of Root(s), 2021', 'CHAO Pei-Yu, Concurrent of Root(s), 2021', 'CHAO Pei-Yu, Concurrent of Root(s), 2021', '', ''),
(56, 'HETEROTOPIA：Dome', '15 min', '*The performance contains flashlights and viewer discretion is advised.', '<p>The concept of Heterotopia was proposed by Michel FOUCAULT in the 1960s. Different from the extreme fictional predictions of Utopia or Dystopia, Heterotopia refers to a space that exists outside the real world while reflecting it. Heterotopia forms the core of this project in which real-world samples are used to create a realistic scene in the micro view that exists but seems illusory.&nbsp;</p><p>In this dome edition, NANONANO reconstructs a macro scene in the micro world. The various possibilities for electron microscopic images are demonstrated through digital images by re-decoding and compiling the electron signal. Combining the characteristics of the dome, this edition provides an immersive viewing experience filled with spectacular landscapes.</p>', '', '', 'NANONANO, HETEROTOPIA, 2021', 'NANONANO, HETEROTOPIA, 2021', 'NANONANO, HETEROTOPIA, 2021', 'NANONANO, HETEROTOPIA, 2021', 'NANONANO, HETEROTOPIA, 2021'),
(57, 'INNERSTAR 01 : Reddening', '15mins', 'Visual Design｜HUANG Wei
Sound Design｜CHENG Dao-Yuan
Realtime Graphic Design｜HUANG Wei, WONG Kuok-Pan
3D Modeling｜Choco TSAO', '<p>INNERSTAR is an audio-visual series co-presented by HUANG Wei and CHENG Dao-Yuan. The concept is based on the relationship between the universe and mind, inspired by astronomical phenomena and the exploration of consciousness and existence from a philosophical perspective. 
INNERSTAR 01: Reddening is the first work in this series. Reddening refers to the interaction between interstellar matter and light, resulting in scattering and wavelength shifts. Using relevant data and physical characteristics as the reference basis for visual and sound, an audio-visual immersive experience is presented with surround sound and dome projection. Soaked and enfolded with a dazzling, illusive atmosphere, viewers are able to be in the deepest space in their minds. The stars are in your heart, and you are the universe.</p>', '', '', 'HUANG WeiＸCHENG Dao-YuanＸWONG Kuok-Pan, INNERSTAR 01 : Reddening, 2021', 'HUANG WeiＸCHENG Dao-YuanＸWONG Kuok-Pan, INNERSTAR 01 : Reddening, 2021', '', '', ''),
(58, 'Night Walk', '8 mins', '', '<p>Lying in a room, looking up at the ceiling, the soul walks out the door, into the mountains.

This film starts with an insomniac landscape as the ceiling of a room slowly emerges. Messy lines move about in the dark, floating and exploring like a ghost in the house. Outside, there are street lights and car lights. The sounds of cars become distant while walking toward a forest. At the end of the film, the audience leaves, bringing a dream with them.</p>', '', '', 'CHUANG Ho, Night Walk, 2021', 'CHUANG Ho, Night Walk, 2021', 'CHUANG Ho, Night Walk, 2021', 'CHUANG Ho, Night Walk, 2021', 'CHUANG Ho, Night Walk, 2021'),
(59, 'NTT ╳ C-LAB The Sun', '30 mins', '＊The performance contains smoke and laser lights and viewer discretion is advised.', '<p>The Sun is a collaboration between new-media artist TIAN Zi-Ping and composer Willian KUO. This piece builds on TIAN’s work for the National Taichung Theater - Lab X The Young Artists’ Atelier in 2020. It traces the tacit relationship between technology and humanity. People are more trusting and relying more on the operation and assistance of machines nowadays. Therefore, contemporary technological art embodies a tenderness that originates from the physical senses and is based on human reasoning.</p><p>This artwork coordinates the momentum of circular laser beams and machines to penetrate dancing bodies. The space within a semi-circle creates a surround sound field that resonates with the audience, as dancers act as physical instruments to transcend the space. This new-media dance performance attempts to build a “relationship” through untouchable visuals and interactions. The intention is to verify the dance and coexistence of machines and physical bodies, which might fundamentally be formed by asymmetrical communication.</p><p>Director｜TIAN Zi-Ping<br/>Sound Designer｜William KUO<br/>Choreographer &amp; Performer｜HSU Chen-Wei, LIN Yi-Chi<br/>Light Designer｜LIU En-Ting<br/>Smoke Designer｜LIN Shu-Yu<br/>Costume Designer｜CHEN Yi-Ting<br/>Technical Director｜TSAI Chi-Hung<br/>Coordinator｜KANG Chao-Tsung, HSIAO Ho-Hsuan<br/>Consultant｜TAO Ya-Lun<br/>Co-Production｜National Taichung Theater, Taiwan Contemporary Culture Lab (C-LAB)</p>', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(60, 'Exploring the Starry Night-Stargazing Lecture', '45 mins per session', '', '<p>Stargazing apps are very useful, providing information about the night sky, such as how to recognize bright stars, constellations, and planets.
 
With a dome screen and the planetarium software Stellarium, an all-new method of introducing the constellations is created, which breaks through the limitations of time, light pollution, weather, and physical space. Moreover, audiences learn about astronomy from different perspectives, such as culture and popular science. With Stellarium software, it is not necessary to have a telescope to observe the surface of the moon, the large red spot on Jupiter, or the rings of Saturn, or to understand the solar system. In the urban jungle, it is possible to see the Milky Way, to learn about the stars, and to gaze at the starry sky!</p>', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(62, 'Opening Video', '-', '', 'The opening video of FUTURE VISION LAB 2021 by 9 Grid Design', '', '', '9 Grid Design, Opening Video of FUTURE VISION LAB 2021', '9 Grid Design, Opening Video of FUTURE VISION LAB 2021', '9 Grid Design, Opening Video of FUTURE VISION LAB 2021', '', ''),
(63, 'Encoding/decoding', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>《Let Me Tell You a Story》/&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">LCD screens,&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">digital images,&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">computer program / 2020</span><br/></p><p>&nbsp;《Aphasia Series 1》/&nbsp;LCD screens,&nbsp;digital images,&nbsp;computer program / 2019<br/></p><p>《Aphasia Series 2》/&nbsp;LCD screens,&nbsp;digital images,&nbsp;computer program / 2019</p><p>《Drifting City》/&nbsp;LCD screens,&nbsp;digital images,&nbsp;computer program / 2020</p><p>《Invalid Perception》/&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">LCD screens, sensors, electronic components, digital images, computer program / 2021</span><br/></p><p>《Misty Island》 /&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">dual channel projection,&nbsp;</span><span style="font-size: 14px;">computer program / 2021</span><br/></p><p>The world we see every day is compiled by coding programs. This seems to be the future scenario predicted by science fiction, but we are already in it.

After being coded in different programming languages, digital codes are understood in data forms such as numbers, text, images, coordinates, and sounds. During the encoding and decoding process for different codes, human understanding of language and perception has changed. Stuart HALL has proposed studies of media hegemony and cultural issues under the media’s communication model. HALL’s research has shown how media producers can “encode” an object, a feeling, and an idea to achieve the purpose of communication. In contrast, “decoding” is the process and method of how the receiver understands after translating the encoded media message.

However, under this overwhelming information overload in the technology and media, how will the hidden encoding/decoding process transform language translations? How can humans find their way to decode after all digital data has been encoded? As technology and media reshape communication and languages, will people still view the world in its true form?</p>', '', 'LCD screens, sensors, electronic components, digital images, computer program, dual channel projection', '', '', '', '', ''),
(64, 'Big Dada: Public Faces', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>Big Dada: Public Faces is a visual narrative comprised of ten AI-synthesised deep fake monologues featuring celebrity influencers from the past and present. The Big Dada series was first released in conjunction with the Spectre installation in June 2019 and included Mark ZUCKERBERG, Kim KARDASHIAN, Morgan FREEMAN, and Donald TRUMP. 

It quickly went viral and led to global press coverage and confused responses from Facebook and Instagram regarding their policies on synthetic media and computational propaganda. The Public Faces iteration was created in 2020 and added new character studies, including Marcel DUCHAMP, Marina ABRAMOVIĆ, and Freddy MERCURY.</p>', '', 'AI-generated video loop', '', '', '', '', ''),
(65, 'Let Me Tell You a Story', '147x172x15 cm', '', '<p>We are in a chaotic encoding world. "Let Me Tell You a Story" discusses how a story is understood. The artist sets up an invisible bystander in the space through programming language, listens quietly and puts together fragments of the event, trying to decode the full picture of a story in different contexts.</p><p>This work uses Machine Learning (ML) and Natural Language Processing (NLP), both of which are used to process language features in artificial intelligence. Like Siri, Google Assistant, and even our commonly used instant messaging software in our daily lives, there are a large number of natural languages to train computers to help deal with the needs of human life.</p><p>In this work, I collect the recorded words and sounds in daily life during the half-year period, especially sounds. I converted the records of conversations with people in daily life into words, and collected these words into a dataset of stories.</p><p>I use a natural language model to train this dataset, using the GPT-2 (Generative Pre-trained Transformer-2) model, which mainly deals with how to let the machine learn the architecture and patterns of human language. We can imagine how humans teach a child to read a story, from the structure of words and sentences, and even understand the meaning of the text and the text emotions of a dialogue. We are training computers to understand human language and regenerate new language systems. The most common of this category is the early automatic paper generation system, or the fake paper or fake news generation system that is common in recent years, which can automatically generate specific articles through the machine learning dataset.</p><p>I used GPT-2 to train the computer on the text I recorded during the six months. As an invisible bystander, the computer listens quietly and tries to piece together fragments of the story. The different brightness of the text in the work shows the training intensity of different sentences. The higher the contrast of the text, the higher the proportion of training times. On the contrary, if the number of training is less or the intensity of the sentence is lower, its color will be lighter.</p><p>This work attempts to respond to the rapid encoding and decoding process in digital media, and the authenticity of the story seems to be increasingly blurred. If we continue to allow computers to intervene in our language system through Machine Learning (ML) and Natural Language Processing (NLP), what will the full picture of a story look like? This is what I am curious about.</p>', '', 'LCD screens, digital images, computer program', 'Let Me Tell You a Story
LCD screens, digital images, computer program
147x172x15 cm
2020', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', '', ''),
(69, '“Aphasia” Series 1', '147 x 86 x 15 cm', '', '<p>The "Aphasia" series discusses that we receive a large amount of information every day and translate it into a special scene through programming language. The work attempts to interpret the indescribable dilemma of receiving huge amounts of information in our daily lives.</p><p>In my daily life, I deal with a large number of letters or text messages every morning after I get up and turn on my mobile phone or computer. There is often a dilemma that faces a series of text but it is difficult to read. All I see are many symbols. Although we have very convenient digital tools to process text and messages, we cannot interpret these texts. It''s like an "aphasia" situation.</p><p>In the medical definition of "Aphasia", most of them are caused by the loss of language ability after the injury of the left brain. Ironically, people who seem to be healthy, when receiving huge amounts of information frequently, gradually fear these words, and even resist reading and communication.</p><p>In the "Aphasia" series, I imported the text data compiled in "Let Me Tell You a Story" and transformed it into geometric symbols through programming language. Although these words have rich meaning, they become symbolic and lose their original interpretable language appearance.</p><p>The reason why we can understand the meaning of language, like the Chinese character "人", is because we define this symbol as "person" and has its meaning. A-Z in English is also defined as a meaningful symbol. However, if the language loses its original meaning and becomes just a symbol, just as we see many meaningless symbols in the image of the work and fill our vision with strange scenes. It presents the "aphasia" which refers to the dilemma that we cannot read the language.</p>', '', 'LCD screens,  digital images, computer program', '“Aphasia” Series 1
LCD screens,  digital images, computer program
147 x 86 x 15 cm
2019', 'Exhibition view', '', '', ''),
(72, '“Aphasia” Series 2', '147 x 86 x 15 cm', '', '<p>The "Aphasia" series discusses that we receive a large amount of information every day and translate it into a special scene through programming language. The work attempts to interpret the indescribable dilemma of receiving huge amounts of information in our daily lives.</p><p>In "Aphasia" Series 2, I tried to discuss the relationship between language and graphics. In the digital age, we prefer to communicate with machines or humans using graphics rather than words. If the language is difficult to read, or we gradually lose the ability to read, what will it look like if we transform the language into graphics?</p><p>I gave the computer the power to construct the symbol. After I define a rectangle in the screen, the color, texture, and flow method of the two lines in the middle of the screen are all determined by the programming language. I only give it the basic principles to make the computer program encode visual communication. I installed a computer on the left side of the screen of the work. At the same time, there is a signal cable and power cord connected to the screen, which is different from the common hiding of the computer and cables behind the work. At the beginning of this series of works, the role of the computer has gradually become a creator. It cooperates with me to create visual elements through programming languages. I try to highlight the idea of co-creation between humans and computers and advance the position of the key role of computers. Try to make the computer seem to be part of the work.</p><p>The works of the "Aphasia" series try to discuss the massive information overload of today''s technology, and language may no longer be what we originally imagined. If the dominant language of the future is no longer human, we will not be able to control the structure of the language we are familiar with. It may also be gradually lost in the gap between language and symbol translation.</p>', '', 'LCD screens, , digital images,  computer program', '“Aphasia” Series 2
LCD screens, , digital images,  computer program
147 x 86 x 15 cm
2019', 'Exhibition view', '', '', ''),
(73, 'Drifting City', '147 x 250 x 15 cm', '', '<p>"Drifting City" discusses the movement of humans on digital maps through the encoding of GeoMedia through digital trajectories. It looks like an autonomous digital spiritual journey, which may also be changing our imagination of distance. It is not only a physical sense of distance, but also a spiritual sense of distance.</p><p>What is digital trajectory? Our mobile phone can record the latitude and longitude coordinates of the movement. These coordinate values can construct all paths through GeoMedia. After collecting the trajectory of more than 2880 days in 8 years, I tried to represent it as a digital image. If the future vision and media are generated by digital coordinates generated by the movement of the body, it will be a new kind of imagination.</p><p>The main topic that I attempt to deal with in this work is the relationship between "body", "memory" and "distance". Discuss how to use the experience of body movement as an element of visual composition through the moving coordinates. A large number of digital coordinates accumulated in this work for 8 years also record the events experienced in these areas. Use my body movement and the memory in the digital trajectory to describe the vision generated in these paths.</p><p>There is another meaning in these digital trajectories, which makes a change in the way memories are recorded. In the past, I often used image-based methods to organize all memories, such as photos and videos. But through GeoMedia, we can wander in these memory-filled paths through these digital trajectories. Our sense of body between movement, distance and memory in physical or virtual space will be redefined.</p>', '', 'LCD screens, digital images, computer program', 'Drifting City
LCD screens, digital images, computer program
147 x 250 x 15 cm
2020', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', ''),
(74, 'Invalid Perception', '147 x 300 x 15 cm', '', '<p>"Invalid Perception" discusses the appearance of the world in which humans rely excessively on the numerical analysis of sensors. After long-term dependence on all perceptions being digitized, are we more ambiguous about the relationship between people and the world?</p><p>We are in the process of using a large number of sensors to perceive the world. We use digital sensors to understand temperature, humidity, and distance. We have gradually lost the basic ability to feel the world. For humans, there are various units of measurement, such as 100 cm, 30 degrees Celsius and so on. But for the sensor, when the unit of weight and measurement is removed, it can use its method to describe the outline of the world with programs and digital signals, which is different from the mode defined by humans and portrays a new world view. .</p><p>Try to imagine if we are used to viewing the screen or the sensor from a one-way perspective, whether there is a chance that the screen and the sensor will describe the world from their perspective. The work is embedded in a screen through more than 800 ultrasonic sensors. It can sense the number of people in front of it and the spatial distance in real time, and the values they sense will be transmitted to the computer in the middle through the signal line. After real-time calculations by the program, the screen on the side will draw abstract paintings to show what they have observed.</p><p>For these sensors, the world they perceive is different from ours. I give them part of the power to describe the world. I only give them simple programming logic and more flexibility. It''s like an artist using painting to describe the world in his eyes. If there is a large number of people moving in front, the lines of the painting will be richer. On the contrary, it will only depict a small figure with a small area when no one is in front. It will restart the painting if no data is sensed for a period of time. The lines depicted in this work are changing at any time. It is like a digital painter who is constantly drawing, and will automatically save the picture files regularly.</p><p>"Invalid Perception" proposes that the future world may be different after humans continue to transmit various data to computers. At the meantime, the master-slave relationship between humans and computers may also exchange roles with each other. Perhaps, we have gradually lost the ability to perceive this world and even the dominance.</p>', '', 'LCD screens, sensors, electronic components, digital images, computer program', 'Invalid Perception
LCD screens, sensors, electronic components, digital images, computer program
147 x 300 x 15 cm
2021', 'Details of the work', 'Exhibition view', '', ''),
(75, 'Misty Island', 'dimensions variable', '', '<p>"Misty Island" uses daily photos and digital programs to create a vision of the future world. It is discussed that when we have over-relied on digital technology to identify and analyze this world, we may be trapped in the midst of confusion and ambiguities caused by digital programming. Perhaps we may enter the "Brave New World" written by Aldous Leonard Huxley.</p><p>I took the scenes that I had visited in my daily life, such as the appearance of the woods when climbing, and the view of the sea from the top of the mountain. I used these images to recreate the appearance of the future world through digital programming. In these reorganized scenes, there will be an image of human faces that are objectively understood by humans. For computers, this is not a human face, it is just the serendipity of the image reorganized through a program algorithm, and only humans will think it looks like a human face. When the computer is capable of determining the future worldview, it may be as shown in the work: blue water is not water and pink mountains are not mountains. It is completely out of human understanding. In this work, the visual images and colors are the results of computer programs. I only provide photos of my daily life and let the computer determine the possibilities. This also proposes that when the relationship between humans and computers is inseparable, we always copy human values through artificial intelligence(AI) and machine learning(ML). If such a contradictory relationship continues, the imagination of the world in the future may face a weird sense of doomsday.</p><p>How can humans find a way to decode if we continue to be immersed in digital encoding in our life patterns. When the technology media reshapes a new language structure, is the digital world we live in not real?</p>', '', 'dual channel projection, computer program', 'Misty Island
dual-channel projection, computer program
dimensions variable
2021', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', 'Exhibition view', ''),
(77, 'TEST', '', '', '<p>TEST</p>', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(78, 'Sunset of Lak-Tshat', 'W220×D120×H150 cm', '', '<p>Sunset of Lak-Tshat reinvigorates the contemporary “sunset” imagery that has long been regarded as a mere clichéd symbol, giving it a fresh materialization, while it also recalls the retro-futurism characteristic of the 2010s internet subculture, Vaporwave. In this installation, the intentional employment of a fog machine accelerates the decay of the smooth, lacquered surface of the iron billboard. As time elapses, the varnish breaks down, and the “picture” ends up being more and more like an “object.” The wordplay “lak-tshat” in Taiwanese signifies the deterioration of the varnish on the surface, while also suggesting errors or imprecision.</p><p><br/>Expanding upon his previous exploration of fictive historicity, Lee Yung-Chih began experimenting with metal corrosion in 2022 as he delved into the relationship between material decay and perceived meanings. The misty and moist Sunset of Lak-Tshat appears particularly ambiguous and bewildering. It refers to a sense of loss for fleeting moments, meanwhile conveying an artificially constructed historicity. Nowadays, we are distant from the profound melancholy expressed in Tang-dynasty poet Li ShangYin’s imagist line, “The sunset is magnificent / But dusk is near.” Contemporary media culture converts everything into rapid consumption of commodified sentiments. Sorrow is transformed into a genrefied experience, as if it were a playlist of emotions for us to play at any time in infinite loops.</p>', '', 'Baking Enamel Iron Plate, Metal Support, Fog Machines', 'Sunset of Lak-Tshat', 'Sunset of Lak-Tshat', 'Sunset of Lak-Tshat', 'Sunset of Lak-Tshat', 'Sunset of Lak-Tshat'),
(79, 'Excavation Site: Potato-shaped Stone Tool (Bat-like Relief), Dum', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>A sunken hollow in an undulating terrain—this large-scale installation created by Hsu Chih-Yu brings forth an almost preposterous question: Is there not a resemblance between an archaeological excavation site and a skate park?</p><p><br/>We are naturally compelled to reflect on how archaeologists and skateboarders each engage with a sunken terrain in their unique ways. The analysis of historical evidence by archaeologists demands physical exertion, and their investigations result in the emergence of new landscapes. In contrast, skateboarders operate exclusively above the ground. As they perform repetitive bodily motions, they assimilate themselves into the sunken terrain. Regardless of whether it involves labor or sport, a compact hoe or a board mounted on four wheels, the body aided by instruments persistently forges new relations to the spatial-temporal connotations of a landscape.</p><p><br/>Hsu’s art masterfully rearranges familiar objects, symbols, and styles, thereby unlocking the potential for varied imaginings and alternative ways of seeing. The latest installation work commissioned by the exhibition juxtaposes and connects two seemingly unrelated scenarios. Presented before us are an archaeological excavation site and a chamber for displaying fabricated antiquities; simultaneously, it serves as an authentic skate park—a playground for exploring concepts in a back-and-forth manner, exchanging roles, and cultivating unbridled creativity.</p>', '', 'Installation', 'Installation', 'Installation', 'Installation', 'Installation', 'Installation'),
(80, 'Printed Sunset', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>We see two couple-like characters snuggling up to each other and enjoying the sunset over the horizon. As the camera zooms in on them, they share a relaxing intimacy with their attention concentrated, as if they don’t want to miss the most touching scene in the last minute of the day. When we focus on their eyes that gaze into the distance, we can’t help but recall: all this appears somehow familiar, exactly a common trope in romance movies. Then, with the change of shot, the camera zooms out from the sunset, and we soon realize that it’s merely part of the studio setting, a cardboard backdrop drawn with vector patterns. However, just like the characters who inhabit their roles, we’re still driven by our vision and the images, trying to stretch our romantic imagination.</p><p><br/>In Printed Sunset, the artist extracts the cinematic trope which conveys a sense of déjà vu, and he arranges it into a minimalist, syrupy yet deadpan flash fiction. The zoom-in/out lenses alternate slowly with each other. They create an impression of paying tribute to the shot/reverse shot often seen in Hollywood films, whilst simultaneously reveal a harmonious, mirror image-like visual structure. Amidst the infinite reflections, we seem to be trapped in a time loop formed by the cinematic trope, which is reminiscent of a repeatedly skipping soundtrack.</p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);"><br/></span></font></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Performers</span>&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Zoé TULLEN</font></p><p><font size="2">Bettina Blanc PENTHER</font></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Music</span>&nbsp; |</font></p><p><font size="2">The Caretaker</font></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Camera</span>&nbsp; |</font></p><p><font size="2">Francisco MECE</font></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Editor</span>&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Andrés BARON</font></p>', '', '16mm Transferred to Digital File, Color, Sound', 'Printed Sunset', 'Printed Sunset', 'Printed Sunset', 'Printed Sunset', 'Printed Sunset'),
(81, 'In the Air Tonight', '11''03''''', '', '<p>There’s an urban legend about Phil Collins’ inspiration for his 1980 hit “In the Air Tonight,” which Artist first heard as a teenager while getting high in a friend’s basement. According to the ritual of the legend, the song is played while a narrator tells the story, syncing the infamous analog drum break of the song with the climax of the narrative.</p><p><br/>In March 2020, from a hillside home that faces the Hollywood sign, he began to dwell on Phil due to an experience he had one night on the Pacific Coast Highway. Driving alongside him was a woman tuned into the same radio frequency, emphatically singing along to “In the Air Tonight.”</p><p><br/>Andrew Norman Wilson created a lengthy overture to this hit in this film. The monologue meticulously narrates the urban legend about this song in a soothing voice like a spiritual mentor. The monologue continued till Phil Collins directly sings the chorus: “Well I remember, I remember don’t worry. How could I ever forget? It’s the first time, the last time we ever met…”</p><p><font size="2"><br/></font></p><p><font size="2">Writter, Director, Editor, and Producer&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Andrew Norman WILSON</font></p><p><font size="2">Narration |</font></p><p><font size="2">David GEORGE</font></p>', '', 'HD Video', 'In the Air Tonight', 'In the Air Tonight', 'In the Air Tonight', '', ''),
(82, 'Long Distance Highway Hotel', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>This work is a collection of familiar clips from road movies: hotel signboards lit up at night, weather-beaten cars, cheap souvenirs, and sleepless nights. In these films, the long journey is portrayed as a mesmerizing coming-of-age ritual. The story unfolds with the scenery outside the car window. The protagonist has a journey as bizarre as profound, on which he not only undergoes a personal transformation, but also finds his innermost self.</p><p><br/>“But do you know what kind of road movie I personally prefer? The ones where the main character has a transformative experience, and remains completely unchanged by the end of the film. Isn’t that cool?” The artist said. We’re not sure whether the idea of “discovering one’s innermost self via a grand tour” comes from the old-school instructions of the real world, or we actually have been living in the narratives of road movies. The artist also highlights the absence of cell phones in all road movies. The out-of-place, palm-sized device disrupts the solitary grand tour, making us constantly aware of the people we love and the friends we miss far away. Eventually, you realize that you can’t be all alone on the road.</p><p><br/>Long Distance Highway Hotel is more than a love letter to road movies. The artist reorganized the symbolic fragments of stereotypical films into a personal fable brimful of fantasies. We’re still on the road, yet this is an unimagined and more vivid road movie.</p>', '', 'Sculpture, Photography, Installation, Painting', 'Long Distance Highway Hotel', 'Long Distance Highway Hotel', 'Long Distance Highway Hotel', '', ''),
(83, 'The Song of Stone', '24’30’’', '', '<p>The Song of Stone is a 16mm film that utilizes the photographs taken by Y. Ernest Satow of LIFE Magazine, depicting Masayuki Nagare’s sculptures and a mason in the village of Ajicho in Kagawa Prefecture while covering a story on the sculptor. Ajicho, with a history of over 300 years, is renowned as the birthplace of the famous “Aji stone.” This film employs a highly figurative visual language to reimagine the lives, beliefs, and work cultures of the 1,200 stonemasons who settled there, growing up amidst the sounds of stone carving. With their own hands, they created their own gravestones, under<br/>which they now rest eternally. Through Toshio Matsumoto’s camera lens, viewers are guided to observe different aspects of the static images. Within the camera frame, the original elements of the images are deconstructed, giving rise to new narratives that establish a mysterious and unique interdependent relationship between humans and stones. In preparation for the filming, Matsumoto meticulously created a highly detailed visual storyboard. Similar to The Weavers of Nishijin, this work brings his theory of avant-garde documentary filmmaking into practice, deliberately disrupting viewers’ perceptions through the complex structure of the film. The soundtrack for this film is composed by Kuniharu Akiyama from the Jikken Kobo, employing musique concrète techniques using sounds produced by stones. It was broadcasted as a television program in February 1963.</p><p><font size="2">Image Courtesty of Postwar Japan Moving Image Archive (PJMIA)</font></p>', '', '16mm Transferred to Digital File, B&W, Sound', 'Image Courtesty of Postwar Japan Moving Image Archive (PJMIA)', '', '', '', ''),
(84, 'For the Damaged Right Eye', '12''10''''', '', '<p>This expanded cinema was performed at the Sogetsu Art Center in 1968. The images were projected onto a single screen using two 16mm projectors and a 35mm projector, resulting in overlapping visuals. During this period, Matsumoto’s works transitioned from the avant-garde documentary to experimental film. Japan in the 1960s was experiencing a societal upheaval, with elements such as disco-dancing hippies, clashes between police and student protesters, the Kwon Hyi-ro Incident, and the exploration of homosexual culture. These societal conflicts of 1968 were vividly depicted on the screen, colliding and blending in multiple layers. At the premiere, strobe lights positioned around the screen were activated at the end. Kuniharu Akiyama composed musique concrète based on popular songs.</p>', '', '16mm Transferred to Digital File, B&W, Color, Sound', 'For the Damaged Right Eye', 'For the Damaged Right Eye', '', '', ''),
(85, 'Engram', '11''50"', '', '<p>This film starts with a Polaroid taken in front of a real scene, where the reality and the image infiltrate and overlap each other. Suddenly a jump cut follows, and the director comes up on the television screen, explaining how images are shaped into our memories. Gradually, the image disintegrates, resulting in ineffective oral communication. Then, another Polaroid shows up. The previous plot repeats itself in a new frame, which seems nonetheless inconsistent with our memories… As Toshio Matsumoto’s iconic experimental short film, Engram, employs a syllogism and a meta-cinematic language to investigate image, reality, and the dialectical relations among different image media. The director himself appears repeatedly in front of the camera, in the picture, and on the television screen. There are frames within frames, everything is tantamount to a recurring yet ambiguous dream. Matsumoto’s late works since the 1980s have focused on the narrative falsehoods of images and the relationship between images and their viewers. “What you treat as reality is fictional, and what you consider as fiction is real,” he claimed so. For Matsumoto, images approximate narratives, whilst a trap lies in such a resemblance, because there are always discrepancies between represented images and realities. The palace of memory constructed by images is little more than a labyrinth.</p>', '', '16mm Transferred to Digital File, Colour, Sound', 'Engram', 'Engram', '', '', ''),
(86, 'Asia and Africa Today', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>After the Korean War, at the United Nations, an annual proposal was held between democratic and communist countries over the issue of U.S. forces stationed in South Korea. As African countries independent from Europe joined the United Nations at the end of the 1960s, many African countries boasted their cohesiveness as non-aligned groups and exerted their power in the UN General Assembly.<br/><br/></p><p>Accordingly, North and South Korea started a diplomatic competition to win support from African countries at the United Nations, and as a result, North Korea received support from African countries at the United Nations from the mid-1970s. By the end of the 1970s, the Soviet Union was providing military aid to Africa and calling it “socialist.” At the same time, China offered African countries military aid as well in exchange for their support for its one-China policy. It is also true that China used Africa as a means to pressure Taiwan.<br/><br/></p><p>In this work, images of gifts scanned from North Korean and South Korean government catalogs are presented as photographs and 3D sculptures. The gifts given to North Korea by its African and communist allies and those given to South Korea by its democratic allies (including the United States) in the 1970s are displayed on a pedestal in the form of an altar. This has the meaning of a ritual for the past, which has already become a relic. In addition, on the projection wall, the propaganda films produced by North Korea, South Korea, and China in the 1970s, as well as the excerpts from the<br/>magazine Asia and Africa Today published by the Soviet Union in the sameperiod, are displayed together.</p>', '', 'Mixed Media', 'International Friendship', 'International Friendship', 'International Friendship', 'International Friendship', 'International Friendship'),
(87, 'Formal Portrait', '8''31"', '', '<p>In Formal Portrait, Polina Kanis reexamines the culture of parades and mass processions as one of the most powerful Soviet ideological instruments, and specifically a deconstruction of the traditional practice of performing acrobatic maneuvers on moving equipment. The key motif becomes the eternity of expectation – we hear the roar of the engine as a symbol of a readiness for action, the pole has been prepared, and the figures obediently come together to form a flag – this endless repetition is fated to remain in eternity, without ever becoming a moment in history. The ritual of the raising of the flag, called upon to demonstrate a victorious strength in a dramatized, directed eternity, merely lays bare the impotency of the action carried out: the flag is raised in an enclosed, publicly unseen territory, its ceremonial raising becomes a metaphor for a victory that will never come. (Text by Daria Atlas, born in 1988 in Moscow. Art historian, art critic.)</p>', '', 'HD Video, Stereo Sound', 'Formal Portrait, 2014, Video, HD, 8’31” ', 'Formal Portrait, 2014, Video, HD, 8’31”', 'Formal Portrait, 2014, Video, HD, 8’31”', 'Formal Portrait, 2014, Video, HD, 8’31”', 'Formal Portrait, 2014, Video, HD, 8’31”'),
(88, 'Teenagers, Smoke and Umbrellas', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>In 2019, Lee Tek-Khean participated in the Anti-Extradition Law Amendment Bill Movement (2019–2020 Hong Kong protests) when he joined the marching crowd in front of the Tsim Sha Tsui Division Police Station. He saw “Sau Zuk (comgrades)” build blockades with found wooden boards to shield the march from external intervention. After the protests, he transported these wooden boards to Taiwan that endured tear gas and police actions. Then Lee used simple, crude woodcut techniques to create prints as re-interpretation of protest images distributed online at the time—a mixture of cellphone snapshots made by “Sau Zuk” at the frontline and journalistic photography in the media. Inspired by Lu Xun’s leftist ideals during the Modern Chinese Woodcut Movement in the 1930s, Lee directly utilized<br/>objects found at protest spots as the material foundation for printmaking and produced this series of prints.</p><p><br/>After the Law of the People''s Republic of China on Safeguarding National Security in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (often referred to as the Hong Kong National Security Law) was passed, the smothering political climate further deteriorated. The series of works planned to be shown in Hong Kong was forced to be taken down because its depictions of slogans and scenes of the protests touched certain political nerves.&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">The&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">exhibition in Tokyo about the protests was, too, cancelled on short notice&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">over concerns for the safety of students and visitors. Afterwards, one after&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">another “Sau Zuk” took down posts on social media or even deleted their&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">profiles for their own safety. Apple Daily, running business for 26 years, and&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Stand News, both ceased their operations because of violating the law;&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">their website disappeared into oblivion. The images referred to by this print&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">series were vanishing rapidly on the internet. The situation could be compared&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">to a brain undergoing memory loss resulting from the elimination of&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">the prefrontal cortex.</span></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">The collapse of the internet image repository placed this print series in&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">the role of preserving evidence that aids in combating forgetfulness. After&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">realizing this, Lee started a crowdfunding project, published a catalogue&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">in 2021, and curated exhibitions to fight against the information blockade&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">on digital media. According to the artist, “Works of art resemble organic&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">systems which generate diverse meanings in various circumstances, all the&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">while witnessing the fall of a city of liberty. Can people like us who are subject&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">to long-term geopolitical risks connect with or find resonance in these&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">works?”</span></p>', '', 'Woodcut, Readymade', 'Teenagers, Smoke and Umbrellas ', 'Amidst the smoke', 'Amidst the smoke', 'Teenagers, Smoke and Umbrellas', 'Teenagers, Smoke and Umbrellas'),
(89, 'Trace', '48.7×60.8 cm', '', '<p>After the incident of radiation leakage from Japan’s Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant caused by the Tōhoku earthquake and the ensuing tsunami on 11 March 2011, Japanese photographer Shimpei Takeda decided to take a physical record of the most serious human-made nuclear accident in history.<br/><br/></p><p>Both visible light and electromagnetic radiation can be adopted to develop photographs since they are similar forms of energy that travel in different wavelengths. Accordingly, Takeda exposed photo-sensitive materials to the&nbsp;traces of radiation emitted from contaminated particles, namely a direct recording of this disaster with cameraless photography.<br/><br/></p><p>In January 2012, Takeda collected 16 samples of contaminated soil from 12 sites around Japan. Then he measured and recorded the radiation levels of these samples. Located in five different prefectures, all these sites, including temples, shrines, war relics, castle ruins, and his birthplace, carry the artist’s vivid memories of life and death. He buried the negatives in these soil samples for weeks or months, allowing the radiation from the soil to leave its mark directly on the negatives.</p><p><br/>This series of images technically presents a materialized topography of the disaster, yet visually they resemble awe-inspiring nebulae. Here, the photo-sensitive technology and the materiality of traditional photography attach a double meaning to this historical experience—both as an immediate relic of the physical world, as well as an extended metaphor for the fragile, infinitesimal human civilization.</p>', '', 'Gelatin Silver Print', 'Trace', 'Trace', 'Trace', 'Trace', 'Trace'),
(90, 'Memory of Currency', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>The project Memory of Currency is an attempt to create money fossils— links between modern currencies and seashells, which were used as currency&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">before modern times. INOMATA inserts a small nucleus—a foreign&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">body—into a pearl oyster shell. Each nucleus is modeled on the portrait of&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">a person used as a symbol on national currency, such as George Washington,&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Queen Elizabeth, or Yukichi Fukuzawa. Inside the shell, the pearl oyster&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">covers the portrait with nacre, creating a pearl in the shape of the individual.&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">The fusing of currency (manmade) with pearl oyster (non-manmade) results&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">in the emergence of a new kind of currency that is inseparable from a&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">natural species. It leaves us contemplating the possibility that these works&nbsp;</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">could one day be rediscovered as fossils by future humans.</span></p>', '', 'Shells, Videos', 'Memory of Currency', 'Memory of Currency (Elizabeth II), Image Courtesy of the Artist', 'Memory of Currency, Photo by Hayato WAKABAYASHI, Image Courtesy of MAHO KUBOTA GALLERY', 'Memory of Currency', 'Memory of Currency'),
(91, 'Gray Room', '16’06’’', '', '<p>In Gray Room, Hsu Che-Yu transforms the dwelling which his late grandmother once inhabited into a digital representation in virtual reality via the means of 3D scanning technology. By doing so, the artist investigates the interplay between architectural space and bodily perceptions as he approaches memories and death through the lens of materiality. Gray Room<br/>unfolds with a childhood memory of the artist, in which he suddenly woke up during sleep and discovered himself outside the house, confronted by a bewildering sensation of unfamiliarity.<br/><br/></p><p>The artist reveals that he has been bothered by unusual headaches in the last two years and that he is diagnosed with Diplopia. Commonly referred to as double vision, Diplopia occurs when an individual perceives two overlapping images while observing a single object, potentially resulting from neurological disorders. Contemporary medical science provides explanations for nearly all cognitive and emotional functions, particularly within the realm of neuroscience. Viewed from a scientific perspective, minds and perceptions regarded as structural dynamics within the nervous system become substantial objects loaded with materialist implications. In Gray Room, intimate family memories are converted into a digital sculpture through 3D scanning. This documentation methodology reminiscent of materialization encourages us to further contemplate the potentialities of emotions.</p><p><br/></p><p><font size="2">Co-production&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Kaohsiung Film Archive VR FILM LAB</font></p><p><font size="2">Han Nefkens Foundation</font></p>', '', 'VR360', 'Gray Room', 'Gray Room', 'Gray Room', 'Gray Room', 'Gray Room'),
(92, 'Hong-ye Juvenile Baseball Team and Teen Images', 'Dimensions Variable, 17’00’’', '', '<p>In 1968, Taiwan encountered its former mother country, Japan, on a baseball field, for the first time in 20 years since the “Retrocession” (to the Republic of China). A series of 5 friendly Taiwan-Japan Little League Baseball Games took place. It was not only the first sport event ever to be televised in Taiwan’s history of television, but also a prelude to the two golden decades where Taiwan frequently won all three championships in the Little League World Series, Senior League World Series, and Big League World Series—a celebratory time for people of this island nation. As we reflect upon history from a distance, now, in 2023, we see images of a group after another group of teenagers serving as a medium to convey the intricate twists and turns of national identity spanning 6 decades.<br/><br/></p><p>Identity is made possible through recurring actions. Nonetheless, the team to kick-start the golden decades—The “Taitung Red Leaves” from Yanping Township, Taitung, Taiwan—is associated with cheating controversies. Their reputation fluctuates in the words of politicians in different eras, reflecting contesting ideologies, while their significance in collective memory fades with time. The “Taitung Red Leaves” as a part of historical literature reveals traces of teenagers’ images complicated by political aspirations, a product of intersecting power deployments.</p><p><br/>Continuing his recent interest in Taiwanese history, Hsieh Yung-Cheng takes the textualized (that is, becoming a part of historical literature) “Taitung Red Leaves” as a starting point and collects images of teenagers from different periods in varied contexts. He then draws upon contemporary gender theories to deconstruct gazes and desires projected onto the teenagers. Through the use of multichannel video and performance in the form of a lecture, he re-interprets the sensory and the perceptive involved in the course of image production and explores the agency of participation in memory writing.</p>', '', 'Video Installation', 'Hong-ye Juvenile Baseball Team and Teen Images', 'Hong-ye Juvenile Baseball Team and Teen Images', 'Hong-ye Juvenile Baseball Team and Teen Images', 'Hong-ye Juvenile Baseball Team and Teen Images', 'Hong-ye Juvenile Baseball Team and Teen Images'),
(93, 'Unmasked (Bootleg)', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>“Cover bands” or “tribute bands” – commonly referred to as “copy bands” in Japan – play famous songs by other people. The difference between both, very roughly, is that “cover bands” arrange the original songs in their own style, whereas “tribute bands” first and foremost adhere to the original versions, and sometimes even “transform” into the original musicians by dressing and acting like them.<br/><br/></p><p>Unmasked (Bootleg) is a portrait of WISS, a band based in Yagi-cho, Nantan-City, Kyoto Prefecture. As a tribute band, they have been playing songs by the American hard rock band KISS for 15 years, and Araki has been following them since two years ago. The way they express their love and respect for KISS through their interpretations of the band’s songs and world view, is in itself a tribute, but they also have their own story. Different from the real thing, WISS is a quintet, and it happened in the past that the members switched makeups and instruments at a live show.<br/><br/></p><p>Presented as a two-channel video installation, the work portrays the band “masked and unmasked” so to speak – onstage and offstage, in performance and in daily life, with and without makeup. It does not include any audio of the live performance, for which there are various reasons, including the idea to highlight the issues of copyrights and reproduction rights that every tribute band is destined to cope with. Araki has realized that it is difficult to discuss this concept as a binary opposition. Copying original songs in a faithful manner doesn’t change anything in the “master-servant” kind of relationship between original and copy. In the question of how it may be overturned, Araki focused on the “essence of the reproduction act itself” that comes to the surface when ignoring the “quality of the performance” that is supposedly what it is all about. While pretending to do a music documentary, the idea was to capture the originality and uniqueness of WISS under the limiting condition that none of their music would be used.<br/><br/></p><p><font size="2">*Commissioned work for Yebisu International Festival for Art &amp; Alternative Visions 2023, organized by Tokyo Photographic Art Museum.</font></p>', '', '2-channel HDV Installation (LED Vision, Silent; LCD Monitor, Sound), Vinyl Record', 'Unmasked (Bootleg)', 'Unmasked (Bootleg)', 'Unmasked (Bootleg)', 'Unmasked (Bootleg)', 'Unmasked (Bootleg)'),
(94, 'Floating Memories', '12''00"', '', '<p>In the nostalgic dreamy video Floating Memories, an old vinyl record, slightly twisted, is slowly spinning. One is caught by this incessantly repeating wave motion and lulled by its delicate sound. Both metaphoric and poetic, the image is reminiscent of a childhood memory, like a distant mirage.</p>', '', 'HD Video, Colour, Sound', 'Floating Memories', '', '', '', ''),
(95, 'Stille Disco', 'L50×W40×H13 (cm), L25×W40×H13 (cm), L46×W40×H13 (cm)', '', '<p>In the nostalgic dreamy video Floating Memories, an old vinyl record, slightly twisted, is slowly spinning. One is caught by this incessantly repeating wave motion and lulled by its delicate sound. Both metaphoric and poetic, the image is reminiscent of a childhood memory, like a distant mirage. The installation Stille Disco consists of an assembly of three stone sculptures, representing a perfect replica of a stereo system, only slightly enlarged. Possibly due to music’s inherently durational quality and its strong connection to emotions, it becomes challenging for us to resist being fascinated by the inanimate, almost fossilized appearance of the rigidly-aligned stone sculptures when they showcase the sound machines as a “still life.” Silent and lifeless, the monotonous characteristics of its materiality and texture convey a sense of timelessness, as though time had halted and unknown intangible nostalgia was transformed into commemorative pieces. The term, “Stille Disco,” refers to a type of events where people dance to music listened to on wireless headphones. In doing so, fascinating contradictions within the term’s semantics are emphasized, where the audience is encouraged to reflect further, while attention is drawn to the subtle distinctions between “sounds-silence” and “motion-stillness.”</p>', '', 'Installation of 3 Stone Sculptures', 'Stille Disco', 'Stille Disco', 'Stille Disco', '', ''),
(96, 'father', '88×111.3 cm', '', '<p>Kanagawa’s father would suddenly disappear, and, if it happened, Kanagawa would not see him for a few months. His father tended to repeatedly disappear and ergo became a man who lost everything－<br/>his money, relationships, and thoughts. Becoming a man with nothing was what he wanted.<br/><br/></p><p>It enabled him not to care about himself and others who care about him. The novelist Paul Auster once wrote: “If it is true that we can ever come to know another human being, even to a small degree, it is only to the extent that he is willing to make himself known. A man will say: I am cold. Or else he will say nothing, and we will see him shivering. Either way, we will know that he feels cold. But what of the man who says nothing and does not shiver? One can do no more than observe. But whether one can make sense of what he observes is another matter<br/>entirely.”</p><p><br/>Kanagawa’s father would shiver if he feels cold, but if you ask him “Why are you shivering?”, then he would answer “I do not know.” We can’t tell whether he really doesn’t know or he doesn’t want<br/>to think. He probably can’t distinguish between them himself.&nbsp;</p><p>Since 2009, Kanagawa had photographed his father—an enigmatic character in his memories.&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">They met regularly. Photography served as the way in which he observed and connected with his </span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">father. These images become the evidence of his father’s previous presence. They hold a detached</span></p><p>gaze at the most intimate moments.</p>', '', 'Inkjet Print', 'father', 'father', 'father', 'father', 'father'),
(97, 'Our Hobby is Depeche Mode', '1:07’00’’', '', '<p>Jeremy Deller and Nick Abraham’s 2006 documentary, Our Hobby is Depeche Mode tells a story of resolute faith and devoted fandom; a bizarre, funny, sad and often touching reflection on how people intimately embrace and appropriate pop culture in their own lives.</p><p><br/>Originally commissioned as part of a planned anniversary release by Depeche Mode’s label, Mute Records, Deller and Abraham’s film exclusively follows the band’s ardent and hardcore international fanbase, documenting their enthusiasms, rituals, and passionate partisanship. As one of their myriad of international fans declares, “It sounds crazy, but it’s our hobby. Depeche Mode isn’t just our passion. Other people go to the gym or do sport. Our hobby is Depeche Mode.”</p>', '', 'Digitised Video Projection', 'Production still showing Depeche Mode fans in Tehran, Iran Our Hobby is Depeche Mode, 2006, Photo by Jeremy DELLER, Image Courtesy of the Artist and The Modern Institute/ Toby Webster Ltd, Glasgow', 'Our Hobby is Depeche Mode', 'Our Hobby is Depeche Mode', '', ''),
(98, 'LEE’S DVD', 'Dimensions Variable, 2’00’’', '', '<p>Welcome to the charming world of LEE ’S DVD! A compact, delightful video rental shop awaits, featuring a collection of hand-drawn DVD mock-ups that blurs the boundaries between 2D and 3D realms.<br/><br/></p><p>“Where streaming is now, DVD rental was the beginning.” Venture into Lee’s Quantum Universe and be captivated by an array of stunning handdrawn DVD mock-ups which is reminiscent of a classic video rental store display. Behold the latest Korean dramas, streaming platform originals, and superhero movies, all recreated in a DIY style, as if they’ve been “burnt” onto DVDs for a fresh and extraordinary audiovisual experience! LEE’S DVD provides not only dazzling film and television works but also an emotional voyage to your past, taking you back to your room in student days where you downloaded video and audio files, sneakily copied and shared them with others. Or, it makes you revisit the era when a mix of games, software, and movie DVD catalogs was a common sight at roadside stands. Enter a<br/>realm where time and space bend as Lee Kan Kyo masterfully reproduces a part of his own memories and those of that era. Witness the creation of a pioneering “origin” technology when the artist compresses the nostalgic elements and transforms them stroke by stroke.</p><p><br/>Through painstaking acts of drawing and painting, Lee reproduces a myriad of mock-ups of visual materials that are overabundant in today’s<br/>capitalist society, such as stills of streaming series, supermarket flyers, and tabloid covers. Closely connected to the LEE Kan Kyo’s N. F. T. and Tsudaya Video Rental series, LEE’S DVD is a part of his artistic trajectory in recent years, while it also pays tribute to the DVD and DVD-burning culture of the “pre-streaming era” in an unconventionally quirky manner.</p><p><font size="2"><br/></font></p><p><font size="2">Painting Assistant&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Serena NAGAI</font></p><p><font size="2">Animation |</font></p><p><font size="2">Midori SAKAKIBARA</font></p><p><font size="2">Clay Sculpture |</font></p><p><font size="2">Honoka TSUCHIMOTO</font></p>', '', 'Keep Case from DVD Rental Shop, Canvas, Paper, Acrylic Paint, Tyvek, DVD Player, Video', 'LEE’S DVD', 'LEE’S DVD', 'LEE’S DVD', 'LEE’S DVD', ''),
(99, 'We Buy White Albums', '1:36''00''''', '', '<p>Created by layering 100 unique copies of The Beatles’ White Album, this 96-minute double LP captures how every copy of the iconic album has been distinctly shaped by its history, both visually and sonically. The half-century-old albums, with scratches and physical imperfections accumulated with age, all play slightly differently, causing the 100 layers to gradually drift out of sync over the course of each side. The gatefold cover and disc labels are composites of the weathered and graffitied originals. Also included is a 24 x 24 inch poster insert featuring images of the individual covers. The 100 original audio tracks used for creating this conceptual album are from the 3,200 copies of The White Album, each with its own pressing number, from the artist''s ongoing acquisition project.</p>', '', 'Vinyl Record, Double LP', 'We Buy White Albums', 'We Buy White Albums', '', '', ''),
(100, 'The Doppelganger Trilogy', '3'' 34", 2'' 50", 2'' 05''''', '', '<p>Slater Bradley’s The Doppelganger Trilogy (2001–2004) conjures up three pop icons from the collective unconscious of our mass-mediated culture. All fallen heroes—two by suicide and one by a protracted descent into disrepute— these figures are perceived through the distancing lens of desire and memory. Each of the three videos is fashioned as a recording of a fauxconcert performance, using a technique reminiscent of what would have been employed to capture the event when it purportedly took place. […] Bradley’s “restagings” of these imagined performances reference specific moments in his own life when he first encountered the work of Joy Division, Nirvana, and Michael Jackson, and through them, the seduction of abandonment, the lure of celebrity, and the erotics of fan worship.<br/><br/></p><p>[…] Since 1999 Bradley has been collaborating with Benjamin Brock, his veritable double, in a series of works that explore the psychologically charged space between one’s self and mirror image. In myth and literature, the doppelganger is an apparition that portends one’s own death, but its form has mutated over time to include the notion of double identity. In the trilogy Brock performs as Bradley playing the roles of Curtis, Cobain, and Jackson. Transformed by costume and posture, and further masked by the deteriorating stock on which he is seen, the doppelganger is at once everyone and no one. What emerges is a triangulation of reflections, an endless hall of mirrors that leads nowhere but to the recesses of the unconscious mind. (Nancy Spector, Curator of Contemporary Art)</p>', '', 'Single-channel Video Projection, HI-8 Video, Super 8 Ektachrome 7240 & Kodachrome 40 transferred to Video, Super 8 Kodak TRI-X Reversal Film 7266 & PLUS-X Reversal Film 7265 transferred to Video', 'Photo by David HEALD, Photo Credit: Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation, New York. All Rights Reserved. Images Courtesy of the Artist', 'Photo by David HEALD, Photo Credit: Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation, New York. All Rights Reserved. Images Courtesy of the Artist', 'Photo by David HEALD, Photo Credit: Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation, New York. All Rights Reserved. Images Courtesy of the Artist', '', ''),
(101, 'I Love Myself And Want To Live', '149.2×92.3×6 cm (Framed)', '', '<p>In 2003, the artist created a photographic work titled <i>I Hate Myself and Want to Die</i>, featuring a portrait of a "doppelganger" that he had worked with for a long time. The figure in the image not only resembles Kurt Cobain, the lead singer of Nirvana, but the title of the work also adopts the name of the band''s eponymous single from 1993. This song was often interpreted as a blunt prediction, as Cobain ended his life with a shotgun the following year. However, Cobain''s true intention in writing the song was, in fact, a self-deprecation—in which he deliberately played with the stereotypical nervous, nihilistic, and world-weary image that the media imposed on him. This underlying tone gave the song a dual meaning, while the artist''s later photographic action added another layer of performativity to the text. This deceased young rock idol thus ambiguously resurrects in the image, as if history is repeating itself—only this time it is a completely fictional narrative, poking at our cultural memory that seems both far away and yet so close. Twenty years later, this photograph is reissued and renamed to <i>I Love Myself and Want to Live</i>, making its debut in this exhibition.<br/></p>', '', 'Giclee print mounted to 2mm Aluminium, Oak', 'I Love Myself And Want To Live', '', '', '', ''),
(102, 'Colonial Pine', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>Intentional alteration of architecture and landscapes has long been an effective means for rulers to promote their ideology and national identity. Such a phenomenon is particularly evident in Taiwan, an island characterized by a multifaceted colonial past. In this ongoing photography series, Kuo captures images of colonial pines in various locations throughout Taiwan. More than just nature photography, these unrefined images depict how a non-native plant is employed by colonial powers, entangling it with intricate political connotations.</p><p><br/>Over the past century, Taiwan’s urban landscape has undergone considerable transformation. Under Japanese colonial rule, sakura and coconut trees are planted by the Japanese government in line with their “Japanization” policy and the objective of positioning Taiwan as a base for Japan’s “southward expansion.” Conversely, the Republic of China (ROC) government has built a substantial number of structures in Chinese style and assigned Chinese names to roads in an effort to emphasize “Chinese culture.” Having been treated differently by the colonizers, the colonial pine seems to carry specific implications within the complex context of Taiwan’s history. Contrary to the majority of needle-leaf trees that necessitate a temperate climate, the colonial pine, native to Australia, adapts effectively to Taiwan’s tropical and subtropical climates. In Taiwan’s low-altitude flatlands, thriving, tall-standing colonial pines create a striking, towering presence. Initially introduced to Taiwan during Japanese rule, it symbolizes the empire’s ambition to use Taiwan as a strategic base for further southward expansion, whereas the ROC government diminishes its association with the south by linking it to authoritative, bureaucratic environments or traditional Chinese gardens. Favored by colonial rulers of various eras and with different political views, colonial pines are planted because of the authority’s deliberate decisions. Today, they can be found in abundance across government agencies, schools, military bases, and public housing. They, too, have once been a popular choice among politicians for Arbor Day celebrations. Kuo’s unrefined documentary photography not only offers a visual record of the tree on this island but also portrays its surrounding environments, as well as the historical and political connotations it embodies.</p>', '', 'Photography, Document', 'Colonial Pine - A Statue, colonial pines are often seen near the statues of many political figures or memorial buildings. Image Courtesy of the Artist', 'Colonial Pine', 'Colonial Pine', 'Colonial Pine - A Camping Site, with organizations like the China Youth Corps and the Boy Scouts, colonial pines spread throughout numerous camping areas and recreational facilities. Image Courtesy of the Artist', 'Colonial Pine'),
(103, 'The Inverted Listening of “Explosive Enemy Aircraft Sounds”', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>The primary inspiration for this piece is a Japanese propaganda record that was commercially released in 1942, titled Collection of Explosive Enemy Aircraft Sounds. This record contained sound recordings of captured American aircrafts flying at different altitudes with the intention to train Japanese youth to be able to detect and distinguish enemy aircraft by their sounds. This record also included a voice track that gave an overview of the enemy aircraft and described their sound characteristics with musical and scientific.</p><p><br/>This record is very well known among Japanese audiences. For record collectors it is a “non-music” oddity that was made during a time when popular music like jazz was labeled as “enemy’s music.” Military buffs fetishize it as a symbol of a lost patriotism together with military songs and military uniforms. Others see it as another example of the desperation of Japan at the end of war, willing to weaponize every part of the body, in this case, the ability to listen, against the modern U.S. army. Namely, the militarisation of music education and perfect pitch training (Numano, 2016) that became the pretext for the production of this record, and the war participation of people with disabilities, particularly visually impaired young students. In each case, however, the actual sounds recorded on the record tell us nothing of this. The sound quality of the recorded aircraft sounds is poor, and the task to distinguish between the jet sounds utilizing musical knowledge seems impossible.</p><p><br/>The Inverted Listening of “Explosive Enemy Aircraft Sounds” poses the question: “How can we hear what is not heard in this record? How can we invert our listening to understand the meaning of this historical record?” The installation consists of sound recordings and artifacts inspired by the “inaudible” aspects of this record. Its aim is to convey a sort of “invert listening” that focuses not on the sounds of the record, but on the historical context and the listening subjects of the record. This work of art also involves the saxophonist Masanori Oishi and the phonograph conservator Ming-Chin Chiu. The former transcribes and plays the sound of the aircraft recorded in the original vinyl record, while the latter casts the original record into a mold, treating the sound groove as the “negative” to be “erected” as a sculpture.</p>', '', 'Mixed media', 'The Inverted Listening of “Explosive Enemy Aircraft Sounds”', 'The Inverted Listening of “Explosive Enemy Aircraft Sounds”', '', '', ''),
(104, 'Happy Valley', '13’00’’', '', '<p>British Colonial-era structures overlook scenes in the aftermath of civil unrest as Hong Kongers work to retain some semblance of normality. The sound of petty arguments from local TVB soap-operas of the 80s is put in concert with captive animals, political graffiti, and desolate highways. Suspension cables and ship anchor lines reveal a fragile urban anatomy, structures that keep the city moving along. As civic functions grind to a halt, the limits of our empathy and control come into question. As the days teeter toward an uncertain future, Happy Valley cinematically probes the role of the so-called “little things.” It’s a rendering of the perseverance of spirit in Hong Kong - an attempt at irony that can’t help but be emotional. Simon Liu captured the leisurely pace of people’s quotidian existence in the midst of the colorful urban landscape of Hong Kong. The traces of Hong Kong’s socio-political turmoil over the past few years are faintly discernible behind the seemingly lyrical, poetic visual language.</p><p><br/></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Film</span>&nbsp;|</font></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);"><font size="2">Simon LIU</font></span></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Producer</span>&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Rachael LAWE</font></p><p><font size="2"><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Sound</span>&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">LiuSeeLiu</font></p>', '', '16mm Film to Digital File (1.43:1 Aspect Ratio), Colour, Stereo Sound', 'Happy Valley, 2020, Images Courtesy of the Artist', 'Happy Valley, 2020, Images Courtesy of the Artist', 'Happy Valley, 2020, Images Courtesy of the Artist', 'Happy Valley, 2020, Images Courtesy of the Artist', 'Happy Valley, 2020, Images Courtesy of the Artist'),
(105, 'Jules Deelder: Dead-Alive', '10’00’’', '', '<p>Jules Deelder: Dead Alive conceived as an installation piece and/or short experimental film enfolds by depicting Jules Deelder, Holland’s legendary performing poet and author, gradually changing in poetic visuals from a living icon into the carrier of his death mask. Babeth Mondini-VanLoo filmed Deelder on 16mm in 1979 for the Bandaged Poets series by New York author Ira Cohen. She used a process specific to the use of a 16mm Bolex camera, a technique that she applied in her expanded cinema projects during the late 1970s and 80s. The screenplay for the film is created through the process of trial and error with image and sound, and the surprises it produces give direction to the narrative.</p><p><br/>Intriguing is the tension between the interaction and the ambiguity of the mask. A strange mixture in what it reveals and hides. Masks in the funerary tradition were not only made to immortalize and venerate the person, they also offered the opportunity to connect and communicate with the spiritual world. It hides the persons as it were, transforms the wearers and accompanies them on their way into the unknown. The recent death of Deelder and the mesmerising soundtrack specially created by one of Deelder‘s musical allies, Benjamin Herman (founder of the New Cool Collective), give new meaning to the material and thus the film offers the possibility to create a fictional space, somewhere between heaven and earth.</p><p><br/></p><p><font size="2">With&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Jules DEELDER</font></p><p><font size="2">Ira COHEN</font></p><p><font size="2">Director, Camera, Producer |</font></p><p><font size="2">Babeth MONDINI-VANLOO</font></p><p><font size="2">Editor, Post-production&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Reinier VAN BRUMMELEN</font></p><p><font size="2">Music Composer&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Benjamin HERMAN</font></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);"><font size="2">FILM ART Production</font></span><br/></p>', '', 'HD Video', 'Jules Deelder: Dead-Alive', 'Jules Deelder: Dead-Alive', 'Jules Deelder: Dead-Alive', 'Jules Deelder: Dead-Alive', 'Jules Deelder: Dead-Alive'),
(106, 'Paper Architecture', 'Dimensions Variable', '', '<p>During the Sunflower Movement in 2014, the two artists, Liao Xuan-Zhen, and Huang I-Chieh, worked with protesters to create an architectural model using recycled materials. Known as the “Paper Architecture,” it was used as a reference map for the protest site and a display stand for promotional materials. With dozens of buildings, event tents, mobile restrooms, and SNG vehicles, the model comprehensively reproduces the streets occupied by the protesters in a simple, unrefined manner.</p><p><br/>“The model is like an epitome of the Sunflower Movement. It is, too, a monument imbued with collective memory,” the artists described. “After we failed to properly preserve it, this model once regarded as an important memorial gradually became dilapidated, almost resembling a scene after a disaster.” For them, the wear and tearof Paper Architecture ironically reflected the indescribable state after the<br/>Movement. Contrasting sharply to the utopian ideas of the occupation Movement, it is more like a depiction of the paralyzed everyday life after a catastrophe.</p>', '', 'Photography', 'Paper Architecture', 'Paper Architecture', 'Paper Architecture', 'Paper Architecture', 'Paper Architecture'),
(107, 'The Parthenon', '600×950×1650 cm', '', '<p><i>The Parthenon</i>, an architectural installation that allows the audience to enter and explore, can be seen as a continuation of <i>Paper Architecture</i>—a cardboard architectural model created collaboratively by the artists and protesters at the site of the Sunflower Movement in 2014—exhibited in Art Space III. Both the naming of the work, <i>The Parthenon</i>, and its sculptural form are reminiscent of the Parthenon in Athens, widely regarded as an enduring symbol of democracy. Nonetheless, unlike the Greek idealism aesthetics, the roof of this building is twisted and columns tilted. Appearing to be on the brink of collapse, it illustrates a scene of our contemporary reality loaded with a sense of crisis. The artwork’s eclectic style draws inspiration from illegal factory constructions frequently observed in Taiwan. Its exterior scaffolding barely sustains the long columns and trusses fashioned from bound cardboard tubes; the temple’s gable and friezes are composed of wooden beams and lightweight steel; the hollowed-out roof is assembled from pieces of cardboard and plywood; and the floor features a collage of drain covers and discarded materials.</p><p><br/></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Through their contemporary adaptation of “the sacred temple of democracy,” the artists intend to revisit the spiritual wasteland of the Sunflower Movement and question how utopian ideals in collective memory end up being a phantom too overwhelming for any individual to bear. They turn such a mental struggle into an art project, connecting a physical place and communal activities. Like the paper model built collaboratively at the site of the Movement, this architecture is completed through the collaboration of many people, including the artists, professional architects, and volunteers who have previously participated in the Sunflower Movement.</span><br/></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);"><br/></span></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">The leftover of the Movement eventually becomes an art project, connecting a physical place and communal activities. For the artists, the very state of seemingly being on the brink of collapse yet still holding together, a state of inconclusivity, reveals something profound: “It does not reject projections of a utopia. Instead, it looks into its regrets, danger, uncertainty, frailty, and possible imperfection during the representation of its grand vision.”</span><br/></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);"><br/></span></p><p><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Team Members</span><br/></p><p><font size="2">Project Lead |</font></p><p><font size="2">LIAO Xuan-Zhen／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">HUANG I-Chieh</span></font></p><p><font size="2">Architectural Design&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">WANG Zhi-Ray／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">TSAI Cheng-Yen</span>／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">LEE Chia-Hua</span></font></p><p><font size="2">Supplier&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">Atelier-3／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Dawen Construction</span></font></p><p><font size="2">Construction Collaboration&nbsp;|</font></p><p><font size="2">YANG Tzu-Hsuan／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">HSU Tsung-Jen</span>／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Yiling CHEN</span>／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">LIN Hsin-I／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">LIANG Chia-Wei</span>／<span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Wayne TENG ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">YANG Chieh-Lin ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">HAN Chia-Chieh ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color);">Rama Saputra ／</span></font><span style="font-size: small; color: var(--primary-gray-color);">CHENG Yu-Yen ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">TSENG Po-Hao ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">KUEH Peu-Gān ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">LIN Ying-Chieh ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">TSAI Chung-Yueh ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Vice City ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">LI TziMei ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Zona</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">HSIUNG Yun-Pei ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">CHEUNG Man-Wah, Franki ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">YANG Hung-Yuan ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">LIN Quei-Chun ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Etta LEE ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Annie LEE ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">LEE Hsu-Pin ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">CHEN Chun-Tien ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Posak Jodian ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">LO Shih-Tung ／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Sophie CHEN</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">&nbsp;／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">LIM Wei-Xiang</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">SU Wei-Hsuan</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Winnie WU</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">Sho Pie</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">／</span><span style="color: var(--primary-gray-color); font-size: small;">CHEN Yueh-Jing</span></p>', '', 'Steel, Timber, Scaffold', 'The Parthenon', 'The Parthenon', 'The Parthenon', '', '');

